“Flea Market” is the third track from Tierra Whack’s debut album Whack World.

On the one-minute track, Whack sings to a significant other who she wants more from in a relationship (or perhaps take it to the next level).

songs.title: Whack World Medley

annotations:
I ain’t tryna rush things
 But, it’s been a while now
 People have names
 And they all smile now

This could refer to women traditionally taking their husband’s last name after marriage. Tierra sees couples around her getting married and being happy, and she wonders when her significant other will propose, since the relationship has been going for a long time.

Get on your knees, baby
 Copy of the keys, baby
 Lovin’ your steez, baby
 Brushin’ off fleas, baby

In these lines, Whack suggest that her love interest should submit and propose by getting on his/her knees. She could also be implying that she wants her love interest to beg for her love and convince her to stay.

The next line suggests she wants a house key. This is a major step in any relationship, which will prove to her that her partner is capable of commitment and wants a serious relationship.

“Steez” is slang for “a person’s distinctive and attractive or impressive style of dress or way of doing things.”

On several occasions, men are referred to as “dogs” as an insult, equating them to being filthy or destructive. The term “fleas” could be playing up on that: she may feel inhibitions about potential infidelity in their relationship and if her love interest will reveal themselves to be a dog. She hopes he/she will rise to the occasion and remain loyal regardless of any of their past mistakes. The “fleas” in this case could also be other people competing for her love interest’s affection, and she compares them to fleas to emphasize their insignificance and pesky presence. Regardless, it is a minuscule concern for her and she is at a point where she is ready to move past it.

Couldn’t wait to see you in a thousand nights
 Easy to see, like a traffic light

These 2 lines are actually mostly unintelligible. Albeit, intentionally so. Tierra Whack’s pre Whack World track “Mumbo Jumbo” is principled off the fact there are no complete words. These two lines are callbacks to the lyrical style of “Mumbo Jumbo” by being indecipherable, a logical conclusion to the idea of “mumble rap.” https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OFNCSbOPxqA

annotations: Make you say “Yo, excuse me miss”

In this line, Tierra references Chris Brown’s 2015 single “Yo (Excuse Me Miss).” The original track discusses getting into relationships and approaching people in the club. Tierra is telling her opponents to treat her with respect and to not test her.
https://www.youtube.com/watch?time_continue=11&v=yn_6LC4loY8
For the dough, I go nuts like Krispy Kreme
Tierra goes crazy for money, or dough. She also uses wordplay to reference American doughnut brand, Krispy Kreme.
Music is in my Billie genes
Referencing Michael Jackson’s hit single from his 1982 album Thriller, “Billie Jean” to state that music is “in her genes.”
Go against me, I’ll beat like Swizz

Swizz Beatz is a Grammy award winning American rapper, DJ, and producer from New York City, New York. He’s worked with some of the biggest names in the music industry from Jay-Z and Beyoncé  to Drake

He’s also married to R&B singer, songwriter Alicia Keys

annotations: Woza
According to the Dictionary of South African English, Woza means to “come” or “come here” and used most commonly by Zulu speakers.
I hate I have to disguise it, why you gotta despise it?

Tierra references severe systemic racism and how it requires black people to code switch to be taken seriously.



While Ebonics is a prominent way to speak in most black families, it is not a dialect that is respected and taken seriously within the mainstream white dominated world. Because of this, many black people must code switch when interviewing for a job or presenting at a meeting (or even if you’re the President of the United States).



Tierra hates that she has to disguise the beauty she sees within black culture, such as Ebonics, just because those outside of black culture “despise” many aspects of black culture.



The line could also be referencing the beauty Tierra sees in dark skin or “ebony.”



Because of Western beauty standards and systemic racism, darker skin is often viewed as unattractive and undesirable. This hatred of darker skin can occasionally drive black people to turn towards drastic and unhealthy cosmetic changes, such as bleaching skin. This is another reason black people feel that they have to “disguise” their dark skin because it is “despised.”
Ebony and ebonics, black people win

Tierra comments on the richness of black culture, by connecting “ebony” and “ebonics” through alliteration.

Ebonics is a slang term for African-American Vernacular English, a version of the English language predominately used by working class African Americans.

Historically, black people have been mocked for their use of Ebonics. However, the irony of this mocking is that Ebonics isn’t a “dumber” way to speak English, just a different way. In fact, Ebonics has just as many grammatical rules and phonological systems as other versions of English.



The line could also be referencing culture appropriation and the “popularity” of black culture.



Black people “win” because of the beauty within their culture. Black people also win because their culture is often mimicked, proving it’s allure.
This that burn, this ain’t no perm

When a perm is applied to hair – it burns. Here Beyonce denies the use of perm knowing it was sold  in the 50’s-60’s to make black people appear more European looking. Beyonce is reclaiming her blackness, her power.

“Boma, boma yé” refers to the formula children from Kinshasa used to cheer Muhammad Ali in his famous “Rumble in the Jungle” fight against George Foreman. “Boma yé” means “kill him” in lingala (one of the four national languages in DRC).

Her alter ego has risen, ask about her, those who have tested her didn’t win against her. She makes sure she’s the last person standing and there are no residual ‘residual feelings’.

She refers to the feud she had with Nuz Queen about being an actual lyricist and a song that was stolen by Nuz Queen from an upcoming artist. She won that battle and continues to win.

Girl of your dreams, Synclaire, Regine
 Turned to the max, can’t forget Maxine

Here, Tierra references the sitcom Living Single, which aired on Fox from 1993 to 1998 and featured a predominantly black cast led by Queen Latifah as magazine editor Khadija James. The series focused on four women and two men who live (or, in Maxine’s case, honorarily live) in different townhouses in the same brownstone building.



Both of Khadija’s roommates⁠—Synclaire (Kim Coles) and Regine (Kim Fields)⁠—attract the attention and affection of men (specifically Obie and Dexter, respectively) and Tierra relates to how men admire them for their beauty, wit, and charm. Moreover, while not officially one of the roommates, Maxine (Erika Alexander) is a strong-willed, acerbic friend of Khadija, who Tierra admires for her audacity and independent spirit.

Her use of the word “queen” in the previous line may also reference Queen Latifah.
